{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti (Laws of Manu), Chapter 5**, argues precisely this in verses 38–40.[^1]\n\nIt declares that \"one who kills it [an animal] for no reason\" suffers \"a violent death in future births\" numbering \"as many hairs as the animal has\" (verse 38). It then states that animals (among other things) \"slain... for the sake of a sacrifice\" by the Self-existent One \"attain higher states of existence again\" (verse 40), adding that \"therefore, in a sacrifice, killing is not killing\" (verse 39).[^2]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 5, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-42b5e1).\n\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 5, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-d81302), [](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-aa01df).",
